\Glsentryfirstplural{rsmt} comprise another class of resently discovered \glspl{mt} that contain an iron-sulfur ([4Fe-4S])-cluster coordinated by a three cysteine CxxxCxxC motif. \Glspl{rsmt} methylate unreactive centers through a radical mechanism \cite{Werner2011}.
Structural evidence suggests, that the mechanism is initiated by reductive cleavage of \sam into a reactive \gls{dado} radical by the [4Fe-4S] cluster \cite{Boal2011,Broderick2014}. 
Three distinct classes (A, B, C) with distinct structural and mechanistic characteristics have been recognized within the \glspl{rsmt} \cite{Zhang2012a}.
The centerpiece of \glspl{rsmt} is the \emph{radical SAM} domain, whose structure was first described in the \gls{rrna} methyl transferase RlmN of \eco \cite{Boal2011}.
This domain consists of an \textalpha\textsubscript{6}/\textbeta\textsubscript{6} partial barrel and contains the [4Fe-4S] cluster, as well as the \gls{sam} binding site ({\autoref{fig:b_mtclasses}).
Class A only contains the radical \gls{sam} domain and includes mainly \gls{rrna} methyl transferases. 
In addition to the radical SAM domain, an N-terminal \gls{cbd} is proposed to be contained in \glspl{rsmt} of class B.
Class B \glspl{rsmt} methylate numerous substrates at unreactive sp\textsuperscript{3} carbon centers, heterocycles and phosphinates.
Class C \glspl{rsmt} most likely contain a C-terminal domain related to the coproporphyrinogen III oxidase HemN in addition to the radical SAM domain \cite{Layer2003}.
Class C enzymes methylate aromatic heterocycles.

Radical \gls{sam} chemistry within enzymes is not confined to just methyl transfer. 
Instead, it has been shown that this type of chemistry is important for a number of rearrangement, cyclization, dehydrogenation, bond-formation and bond-cleavage reactions in nature \cite{Broderick2014}.

\subsection{\textit{S}-Adenosyl-\textsc{l}-methionine}

\Glsentryfirst{sam}, first described in 1953 \cite{Cantoni1953}, is the universal co-substrate for all \gls{sam} dependent methyl transferases.
However, it is not only involved in methyl transfer, but is essential for a myriad of other reactions \cite{Broderick2014}.
This makes \gls{sam} the second most ubiquitous co-substrate after \gls{atp}.

The methyl group of \gls{sam} is partially positively charged due to its position at the sulfonium center and is in consequence highly activated.
The increased electrophilicity of the methyl group makes it a strong alkylation agent. 
Furthermore, \gls{sah} is a good leaving group.
Therefore, nucleophilic transfer of the methyl group of \sam is thermodynamically highly favoured ($\Delta G^0 \approx$ \SI{-70}{\kilo\joule\per\mole} for SAM + homocysteine \textrightarrow~SAH + methionine) and allows the rapid and selective methylation of a range of substrates \cite{Schubert2003}.
The fact that the methyl group is the least sterically hindered of all transferable carbon groups makes a methyl transfer the kinetically most favourable \sntwo reaction (disregarding nucleophile and leaving group).
%
Despite its apparent reactiveness, \gls{sam} is still quite stable at physiological conditions compared to other sulfonium species like the trimethylsulfonium ion, which quickly reacts with nucleophiles and is often used for derivatization prior to GC analytics \cite{Butte1983}.
Meanwhile, \sam is readily cleaved into adenine and \textit{S}-ribosylmethionine under alkaline conditions \cite{Borchardt1979} and other deteriorating processes such as racemization and intramolecular cleavage are to be reckoned with \cite{Hoffman1986}.
%Disregarding nucleophile and leaving group, the transfer of a methyl group is the kinetically most farourable \sntwo reaction.


\sam is produced by the enzyme \sam synthetase (EC 2.5.1.6) from methionine and \gls{atp} in a two step reaction \cite{Takusagawa1996}.
At first \sam is formed and the triphosphate group of \gls{atp} is cleaved off. 
Then, the inorganic triphosphate is hydrolyzed to monophosphate and diphosphate after which the products are released.
The demethylated \gls{sam} is called \glsentryfirst{sah}. 
\Gls{sah} is a common side product of all \sam dependent \glspl{mt} and can be further cleaved by \gls{sah} hydrolase (EC 3.3.1.1) to afford homocysteine and adenosine \cite{Lozada-Ramirez2008a}.
The cobalamine (vitamin B\textsubscript{12}) dependent methionine synthase (EC 2.1.1.13) can remethylate homocysteine to methionine using N\textsuperscript{5}-methyltetrahydrofolate as a methyl donor \cite{Banerjee1990}. 
Taken together, reactions leading from and to \sam are commonly called the activated methyl cycle.

\subsection{Methyl transferase mechanisms}

Non-radical \gls{sam}-dependent \glspl{mt} catalyze the transfer of the methyl group of \gls{sam} to an activated nucleophile.
The methylation reaction proceeds via a single displacement S\textsubscript{N}2 mechanism, through an sp\textsuperscript{2} hybridized transition state and results in the inversion of configuration (\autoref{fig:b_methyl_transfer}).%, with \gls{sah} being a very good leaving group.
