The \sntwo mechanism was proposed early on \cite{Gray1979,Mihel1979}, but only with the development of the chiral methyl group methodology extended mechanistic studies were made possible \cite{Floss1993,Floss1979}.
An elegant method for the synthesis of chiral acetate made use of glycolytic enzymes to convert [1-\textsuperscript{3}H]-glucose via its glycolysis intermediates to [3-\textsuperscript{2}H,\textsuperscript{3}H]-lactate, which is subsequently oxidized by chromiumtrioxide (\autoref{fig:b_chiralacetate}) \cite{Woodard1980}.
The chirality of the resulting acetate can be controlled by the solvents (\cf{D2O} or \cf{H2O}) used during the enzymatic reactions. 
The chiral acetate can be used for the synthesis of e.g. [\textit{methyl}-\textsuperscript{2}H,\textsuperscript{3}H]-methionine.
