In 1980, Woodward \etal fed \textit{R}- and \textit{S}-methionine containing an assymetrical methyl group to cultures of \textit{Streptomyces griseus} and found, that the enzymatic transfer of two methyl groups (\textit{N} and \textit{C}-methylation) during the indolmycin biosynthesis proceeded with inversion of the configuration, strongly implying an \sntwo mechanism \cite{Woodard1980}.
This experiment also demonstrated that, \invivo, [\textit{methyl}-\textsuperscript{2}H,\textsuperscript{3}H]-methionine is converted to [\textit{methyl}-\textsuperscript{2}H,\textsuperscript{3}H]-\gls{sam} before the methyl group is transferred by a \gls{mt}.
\textit{In vitro} experiments that were conducted using \gls{comt} further supported the hypothesis of an \sntwo mechanism \cite{Woodard1980a}.

The nucleophile attacking the methyl group of \sam is usually activated by abstraction of a proton through a general base (e.g. histidine, lysine) \cite{Zubieta2002,Zubieta2001a,Brandt2015} and/or with the help of a lewis acid such as complexed \cf{Mg^2+} \cite{Vidgren1994,Kopycki2008b}.
In a bimolecular reaction, the rate is highly dependent on the concentration of both compounds.
\begin{equation*}
  rate = k[A][B]
\end {equation*}
Low concentrations mean a low rate.
This is in part due to the fact, that bimolecular reactions are entropically disfavoured.
%The combining of two molecules leads to a loss in rotational and translational entropies. 
\Glspl{mt} (and enzymes in general) strongly increase the effective concentration of each compound and thereby decrease entropy, in that methyl donor and acceptor are bound (immobilized) in close proximity to each other in the active site \cite{Fersht1999}.
The right positioning of the substrates is a major factor for efficient catalysis and enzymes go through great lengths to achieve optimal alignment of substrates.
One remarkable example are \glspl{dmt}, which can flip the target nucleotide out of the DNA-helix to provide the best orientation of \gls{sam} and the acceptor nucleophile \cite{Klimasauskas1994}.

Since the reaction catalyzed my \glspl{mt} is a two substrate reaction, kinetics-driven mechanistic studies have been done on a number of different \glspl{mt} to show the binding mode of the substrates.
It turns out, that the reaction mechanism varies for \glspl{mt} from different organisms and classes.
There is no one mechanism that describes every \gls{mt}.
A random bi-bi binding mechanism is for example exhibited by rat liver \gls{comt} \cite{Coward1973}, CheR protein-\textsc{l}-glutamate \textit{O}-\gls{mt} from \textit{Salmonealla typhimurium} \cite{Simms1991} and the protoporphyrin IX \textit{O}-\gls{mt} of \textit{Rhodobacter capsulatus} \cite{Sawicki2007}. 
The protoporphyrin IX \gls{mt} from etiolated wheat \textit{Triticum aestivum} on the other hand shows a ping-pong bi-bi mechanism \cite{Yee1989}, whereas ordered bi-bi mechanisms were shown for the cytosine \gls{dmt} MSpI and isoprenylated \gls{pmt} \cite{Bhattacharya1999,Shi1992}.
Meanwhile, the enzymes exhibiting ordered bi-bi mechanisms were different in that one bound \gls{sam} first and released \gls{sah} last \cite{Shi1992}, whereas the other one bound the acceptor molecule first \cite{Bhattacharya1999}.
Competetive product inhibition, especially by \gls{sah}, is commonly observed for \mts \cite{Ball1972,Simms1991,Shi1992,Bhattacharya1999}.
 
The mechanisms of \glspl{rsmt} are outside the scope of this work, but the interested reader is instead referred to current reviews on the topic \cite{Zhang2012a,Broderick2014}.


\subsection{Plant \glsentryfirstplural{omt}}

%Historically, research on \glspl{omt} has been focused on mammalian \gls{mcomt}, which was the first \gls{omt} described (1958) and structurally characterized (1994) \cite{Vidgren1994,Axelrod1958}.
Plant \glspl{omt} were the prime interest of this work.
As such, plant \glspl{omt} represent a large group of plant enzymes that catalyze the transfer of a methyl group to a hydroxyl or carboxyl group of phenylpropanoids, flavonoids or alkaloids.
\textit{O}-methylation greatly effects the (bio)-chemical properties of a compound and can for example have profound influences on reactivity, solubility, bioavailability, antimicrobial or antioxidant activities.

\Pomts are subdivided into two groups according to their size and the spatial relationship between three highly preserved motifs (\autoref{tab:b_plomts})  \cite{Joshi1998}.
Group I members, containing \gls{ccoaomt}-like representatives, are usually between 110 and 140 amino acid residues shorter than group II members ($\approx$340--390 amino acids).
