In contrast to group II, group I \pomts require \cf{Mg^2+} for activity. Overall, they are fairly similar to mammalian \glspl{comt} \cite{Joshi1998}.
Group II \pomts can methylate a variety of substrates, whereas group I \pomts are usually very strict in their substrate scope utilizing only a couple of substrates.
However, some enzymes from group I are much more relaxed with their acceptance of substrates.
For example, \gls{pfomt} from the ice-plant \textit{Mesembryanthemum crystallinum} and an \gls{omt} from chickweed \textit{Stellaria longipes} can utilize several substrates \cite{Zhang1997,Ibdah2003}.

%In the following paragraphs one enzyme of each class of plant \glspl{omt}  
\paragraph{\protect\Glsentryfirst{pfomt}} is a \cf{Mg^2+}-dependent class I plant \gls{omt} from the ice plant \mesem and was first described in 2003 by Ibdah \etal \cite{Ibdah2003}.
\pfomt was the first class I \gls{mt} that provided evidence showing, that methylation of flavonoids is not only restricted to class II plant \glspl{omt}.
It belongs to a subgroup of class I plant \glspl{omt}, that is distinguished from \glsentryfirst{ccoaomt} by a lower sequence homology and a broader substrate promiscuity and regiospecificity.
\pfomt methylates a number of flavonoids and phenyl propanoids, preferably at the \textit{meta}-position, provided a catecholic moiety is present.
Enzyme purified from its native source \mesem is truncated N-terminally by 11 amino acids, although there is no known signaling sequence \cite{Vogt2004}.
This truncation has deleterious effects on the catalytic efficiency, especially towards substrates such as caffeoyl glucose and caffeoyl-CoA, but also influences the regioselectivity.
There is only speculation as to the purpose of this N-terminal truncation \invivo, but metabolic regulation is plausible.
%The truncated and non-truncated enzymes differ in their temperature optimum, which is located at \SIrange{37}{40}{\celsius} and \SIrange{45}{5}{\celsius} respectively.
%For the native (truncated) \pfomt, the maximal activity is \SI{150}{\micro\molar} \cf{Mg^2+}.

The three dimensonal structure of \pfomt shows a dimeric protein (pdb: 3C3Y) \cite{Kopycki2008b}.
Each monomer exhibits a Rossmann \textalpha/\textbeta-fold consisting of 8 \textalpha-helices and 8 \textbeta-strands.
The catalytically important N-terminus is not resolved in the structure.
\Gls{sah} and \cf{Ca^2+} were cocrystallized and appear bound in the active site. 
\cf{Ca^2+} is complexed by two aspartate and one asparagin residues with the rest of the coordination spaces occupied by waters.


