\paragraph{The industrial potential of methyl transferases} has been demonstrated by several studies \cite{Wessjohann2013}.
Li and Frost \cite{Li1998} presented an environmentally friendly method to produce vanillin from glucose by genetically modified \eco cells. During the fermentation, methyl transfer was achieved by recombinantly expressed \gls{comt}.
Recent developments mainly focus on the synthesis of structurally more complex and highly valuable compounds, especially flavonoids, due to their manifold biological effects (\autoref{fig:b_review}). 
For example, \molnum[ermanine]{ermanine} with a claimed anti-inflammatory and antiviral activity, can be synthesized from its inactive precursor kaempferol (5,7-dihydroxy-3,4'-dimethoxyflavone) by whole-cell biotransformation \cite{Bong2006}. 
Sequential introduction of the two methyl groups was performed by OMT-9 from rice (ROMT-9) and OMT-2 from soybean and resulted in almost quantitative conversion of the substrate. 
Similarly, transformation of kaempferol and quercetin by an engineered variant of the OMT-7 from \textit{Populus deltoides} gave the 3,7-di-O-methyl products in \SI{58}{\percent} and \SI{70}{\percent} yield, respectively \cite{Joe2010}. 
The conversion of naringenin (4',5,7-trihydroxyflavanone) to 3-O-methylkaempferol was per- formed as an enzymatic two-step process involving initial oxidation by flavonol synthase and methylation of the intermediate by ROMT-9 \cite{Eun2010}.

