The most promising approach for the chemoenzymatic production of flavonoids remains the \textit{de novo} synthesis from inexpensive biosynthetic precursors such as p-coumaric acid, which is initially processed into non-methylated flavonoids and subsequently modified by \gls{omt} reactions. 
This way, \molnum[7-\textit{O}-methyl-aromadendrin]{Mearomadendrin} and the corresponding flavone genkwanin were obtained from recombinant \eco in yields of \SI{2.7}{\milli\gram\per\litre} and \SI{0.2}{\milli\gram\per\litre}, respectively \cite{Leonard2006c,Malla2012c}.
Similarly, several non-natural (e.g. fluorinated) cinnamic acids can be converted to mono- and dimethylated stilbenes such as \molnum[3,5-dimethoxy-4'-fluorostilbene]{dimethylfluorstilben} using a reconstructued plant pathway in \eco.

\textit{N}-, \textit{C}- and \textit{S}-methyl transferases have also been successfully used in biocatalytical applications.
For example, \molnum[epinephrine]{epinephrin} and \molnum[\textit{N}-methyltetrahydroisoquinoline]{isoquinoline} were obtained by \invitro and \invivo biotransformations of their respective precursors \cite{MORISHIGE2014,Markoglou2002a}.
Furthermore, a number of studies describe the production of several other \textit{N}-methylated alkaloid and non-alkaloid compounds \cite{Palazon2008a,Rigbers2008a,Zhang2012b}.
\textit{C}-methyl transferases have been used biocatalytically to modify different phenols \cite{Crnovcic2010a} and coumarin derivatives, to obtain compounds such as \molnum[3-(benzoylamino)-8-methylumbelliferone]{umbelliferone} \cite{Stecher2009}.
Also, the composition of the main tocopherol species in plants could be tuned by the introduction of bacterial \glspl{cmt} \cite{Hunter2007a}.
\textit{S}-methyl tranferases have only seen a limited number of biocatalytic applications, but a candidate from \textit{Catharanthus roseus} shows some promiscuous activity towards small aliphatic and aromatic thiols (\molnum[furfuryl-methyl-sulfide]{methylsulfide}) \cite{Coiner2006}. 
